## SOP: Build and Present a Customer Support Analytics and Machine Learning Project

### Objective

This SOP outlines the end-to-end process for analyzing customer support data, building predictive models, creating visualizations, and documenting results in a version-controlled project. The goal is to help a team member produce actionable insights that can improve agent performance and customer satisfaction.

### Key Steps

 

**1. Define the project goal and scope** [0:31](https://loom.com/share/85aeab24c08c420d9fd8a1bdba86a9a3?t=31)

![generated-image-at-00:00:31](https://loom.com/i/ab9dd4beac7146239fbd4eebd566b18a?workflows_screenshot=true)

- State the business objective clearly: analyze customer interaction data to improve agent performance and predict CSAT outcomes.
- Confirm the dataset focus: customer support cases, shift timing, tenure, handling time, and satisfaction scores.
- Define the expected deliverables: 
  - Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA)
  - Machine learning models
  - Visualizations
  - Final insights and recommendations

 

**2. Prepare and inspect the dataset** [1:03](https://loom.com/share/85aeab24c08c420d9fd8a1bdba86a9a3?t=63)

![generated-image-at-00:01:03](https://loom.com/i/750cbfbc551d49a69f1957f952921ea5?workflows_screenshot=true)

- Load the customer support dataset into your analysis environment.
- Review the directory structure and file contents before analysis.
- Identify the key fields needed for the study, such as: 
  - Shift
  - Tenure
  - CSAT score
  - Handling time
  - Agent and manager information
- Check for missing values, formatting issues, and inconsistent column names.

 

**3. Perform exploratory data analysis (EDA)** [1:15](https://loom.com/share/85aeab24c08c420d9fd8a1bdba86a9a3?t=75)

![generated-image-at-00:01:15](https://loom.com/i/f8be046913954774a7d8aaa623e054da?workflows_screenshot=true)

- Analyze the distribution of support cases across shifts.
- Measure variability in customer satisfaction scores.
- Look for patterns in customer support operations that may affect performance.
- Identify trends, outliers, and relationships between operational variables and CSAT.

 

**4. Use Python and Pandas for data cleaning and aggregation** [2:11](https://loom.com/share/85aeab24c08c420d9fd8a1bdba86a9a3?t=131)

![generated-image-at-00:02:11](https://loom.com/i/3d645221989541b3b6af443291092e3b?workflows_screenshot=true)

- Use Python as the primary development language.
- Use Pandas to clean, transform, and aggregate the data.
- Standardize column names and remove hidden spaces or formatting inconsistencies.
- Prepare the dataset for modeling by ensuring the data is structured and usable.

 

**5. Build the first predictive model: Logistic Regression** [2:51](https://loom.com/share/85aeab24c08c420d9fd8a1bdba86a9a3?t=171)

![generated-image-at-00:02:51](https://loom.com/i/dbfd9f61a0f64cb6bf27f4adb722aa33?workflows_screenshot=true)

- Train a Logistic Regression model as the baseline classifier.
- Use it to establish a simple, interpretable benchmark for binary classification.
- Evaluate performance using F1 score instead of accuracy when the dataset is imbalanced.
- Record the baseline results for comparison with more advanced models.

 

**6. Build the second predictive model: Random Forest Classifier** [3:32](https://loom.com/share/85aeab24c08c420d9fd8a1bdba86a9a3?t=212)

![generated-image-at-00:03:32](https://loom.com/i/5586e91d118a405893ac60db3896a384?workflows_screenshot=true)

- Train a Random Forest Classifier to improve predictive performance.
- Use the model to capture non-linear relationships and reduce overfitting.
- Compare its results against Logistic Regression.
- Document the strengths and limitations of the model.

 

**7. Build the third predictive model: Support Vector Machine (SVM)** [3:45](https://loom.com/share/85aeab24c08c420d9fd8a1bdba86a9a3?t=225)

![generated-image-at-00:03:45](https://loom.com/i/443fdf03c7ed49378897a3eb29dcac56?workflows_screenshot=true)

- Train an SVM model as the final candidate model.
- Compare its performance against the other two models.
- Select the model with the best balance of precision and recall.
- Confirm the final model using cross-validation results and F1 score.

 

**8. Select the final model based on performance metrics** [4:10](https://loom.com/share/85aeab24c08c420d9fd8a1bdba86a9a3?t=250)

![generated-image-at-00:04:10](https://loom.com/i/ccdda5d4ce814749aee8187d12badeda?workflows_screenshot=true)

- Compare all three models using the same evaluation metric.
- Choose the model with the highest F1 score and strongest generalization.
- In this project, SVM was selected because it achieved the best tradeoff between precision and recall.
- Document why the final model was chosen over the baseline and alternative models.

 

**9. Create analytical visualizations** [4:36](https://loom.com/share/85aeab24c08c420d9fd8a1bdba86a9a3?t=276)

![generated-image-at-00:04:36](https://loom.com/i/ed027e60e8c14ba58b6622c6f75f2080?workflows_screenshot=true)

- Build a set of visualizations to uncover operational and customer behavior patterns.
- Include charts such as: 
  - Correlation heat map
  - Pair plot for numeric variables
  - CSAT score by shift and tenure
  - Distribution of agent shifts
  - Handling time vs. CSAT score
  - Performance by tenure bucket
  - Distribution of item price and ticket price
  - CSAT by manager, supervisor, and shift
- Use the charts to identify hidden relationships and business drivers.

 

**10. Review and document all chart outputs** [5:34](https://loom.com/share/85aeab24c08c420d9fd8a1bdba86a9a3?t=334)

![generated-image-at-00:05:34](https://loom.com/i/2d6e0048834c4843b512287e19758109?workflows_screenshot=true)

- List every chart created in the analysis.
- Ensure each chart has a clear title, labels, and interpretation.
- Organize the visuals so stakeholders can quickly understand the findings.
- Use the charts to support conclusions about shift timing, tenure, and satisfaction.

 

**11. Troubleshoot data and environment issues** [6:31](https://loom.com/share/85aeab24c08c420d9fd8a1bdba86a9a3?t=391)

![generated-image-at-00:06:31](https://loom.com/i/c66eb96998a8422c9733bc6be1b4b636?workflows_screenshot=true)

- Monitor the analysis for runtime or environment issues.
- Resolve library errors as they appear.
- Fix NLTK tokenization issues by updating the environment with the required Punkt data.
- Investigate and correct key errors caused by hidden spaces in column names.

 

**12. Validate schema and clean column naming issues** [7:10](https://loom.com/share/85aeab24c08c420d9fd8a1bdba86a9a3?t=430)

![generated-image-at-00:07:10](https://loom.com/i/0896b96adecc463082bd13f0ae73058e?workflows_screenshot=true)

- Inspect the dataframe schema using `df.columns.tolist()` or an equivalent method.
- Confirm that all column names match the expected format.
- Remove extra spaces or hidden characters before rerunning analysis.
- Recheck the dataset after fixes to prevent repeated key errors.

 

**13. Summarize findings and publish the project** [7:23](https://loom.com/share/85aeab24c08c420d9fd8a1bdba86a9a3?t=443)

![generated-image-at-00:07:23](https://loom.com/i/32f3a20c2ea143928593f1f5c0e2d189?workflows_screenshot=true)

- Summarize the full workflow: 
  - Data cleaning
  - Model training
  - Visualization
  - Version control
- Explain how the project supports a data-driven dashboard for improving agent coaching and customer experience.
- Save and maintain the final work in GitHub for version control and reproducibility.
- Prepare the final presentation or report for stakeholders.

### Cautionary Notes

- Do not rely on accuracy alone if the dataset is imbalanced; use F1 score for model comparison.
- Verify column names carefully before modeling to avoid key errors from hidden spaces or inconsistent formatting.
- Ensure required NLP resources are installed before running tokenization steps.
- Confirm that all charts are interpretable and labeled clearly before sharing with stakeholders.

### Tips for Efficiency

- Clean and standardize column names early to prevent repeated debugging later.
- Use a consistent evaluation metric across all models for fair comparison.
- Save intermediate outputs and notebooks frequently to preserve progress.
- Build visualizations after cleaning so charts reflect reliable data.
- Keep GitHub commits small and descriptive to make version control easier to manage.

